    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-06-15T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-06-15T00:00:00-05:00" n="395"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d395">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">763.72/1867½</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> ad interim
                        to President <persName type="to">Wilson</persName>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-06-15">
                            <hi rend="italic">June 15, 1915</hi>.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Dear Mr. President</hi>: I enclose a memorandum which the
                    British. Ambassador handed me yesterday, requesting copies of sworn declarations
                    of the United States customs or other officers who examined the <hi
                        rend="italic">Lusitania</hi> prior to her departure from New York, for the
                    use of the British Government in connection with the <hi rend="italic"
                        >Lusitania</hi> inquiry. I am informed by the Treasury Department that the
                    reports of the Collector at New York are in your hands.<note n="21"
                        xml:id="d395fn1">See <ref target="#pg_428">p. 428</ref>.</note> I therefore
                    venture to ask if you perceive any objection to having copies of the Collector’s
                    whole report, or certain portions of it, made and sent to the Ambassador, in
                    compliance with his request. It may be that the Collector’s report is in such
                    shape that it would be more convenient to ask the Treasury Department to obtain
                    sworn statements of the customs officers, covering the particular points
                    mentioned by the Ambassador in his memorandum.</p>
                <p>Very sincerely yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Robert Lansing</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
                <pb facs="0520" n="452" xml:id="pg_452"/>
                <frus:attachment>
                    <opener>
                        <seg rendition="#center">[Enclosure]</seg>
                    </opener>
                    <head>
                        <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the British Ambassador</hi> (<hi
                            rend="italic">Spring Rice</hi>)</head>
                    <p>Is there any objection to communicating to the British Government for use in
                        connection with the <hi rend="italic">Lusitania</hi> enquiry copies of sworn
                        declarations of U. S. customs or other officials who examined the vessel
                        prior to departure from New York, describing precise nature of their
                        inspection and stating whether or not there were any guns on board and
                        whether or not the vessel carried any explosives. [<hi rend="italic"
                        >?</hi>]</p>
                    <closer>
                        <dateline rendition="#left">
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                            </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-06-14">
                                <hi rend="italic">June 14, 1915</hi>.</date>
                        </dateline>
                    </closer>
                </frus:attachment>
            </div>
